The Root of the Crime, Putin
Moscow—German, French, and Swedish medical experts have unanimously concluded that Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is the biggest opponent of Russian President Putin and also the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, because Navalny survived, the relations between Russia and Germany did not deteriorate.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," German Chancellor Merkel declared that Navalny is a "victim persecuted for freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is very serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasized that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel called on Russian authorities to conduct an independent and transparent investigation.
The EU and the UK also support this call.
If the investigation proves that the Russian government is the main culprit behind the incident, the European Commission will impose a new round of sanctions.
Regardless, poisoning is prohibited under the provisions of the Chemical Weapons Convention.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok against its political opponents.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergei Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both survived and went into hiding.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
On the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesperson Dmitry Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to blame the Russian government."
Sergei Naryshkin, the head of the Russian Foreign Intelligence Service, even claimed that it was the act of Western intelligence agencies, attempting to tarnish the Russian government's reputation.
Naryshkin's statement is clearly a stretch, but he also points out a fact: the Navalny incident is more harmful than beneficial to Russia.
Poisoning a prominent political opponent just before an upcoming election, and using a toxin developed by the former Soviet Union, is simply indefensible.
Especially given that the people of neighboring Belarus are protesting the August elections, this timing is even more intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial response to the Navalny incident was particularly confusing.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before committing the crime?
If, as Germany claims, the Russian government was indeed responsible, this murder would also be a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader of the international political stage (the top antagonist in the "Star Wars" films), intervening in the U.S. election, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK into Brexit, and propping up Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB officer, he is shrewd, far-sighted, and cunning.
Why couldn't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why was Navalny able to flee to Germany, and why was he quickly diagnosed as having been poisoned?
Now, Putin faces international condemnation and sanctions, and the second phase of the Nord Stream gas pipeline to Germany is at risk of cancellation.
This murder is clearly a costly failure.
In fact, this has further fueled public opposition to the Russian authorities' misconduct.
Even if it was not Putin who did it, the claim that Western intelligence agencies are responsible is even more absurd.
If such accusations are proven true, scientists from Germany and Sweden would not have disclosed the fact that the nerve agent used was Novichok.
More likely, the plot was orchestrated by Putin's inner political circle.
Perhaps Putin needed Navalny to stop speaking out before the election, or perhaps it was his anti-corruption investigations that caused the trouble.
In Russia, you can buy a variety of products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's political enforcers, though loyal, are foolish; they believed poisoning Navalny was a good idea, and only a few involved know the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts have similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Murza was the coordinator of the Khodorkovsky Open Investigation Committee.
The poisoning of Peter Verzilov, publisher of the independent news website Mediazona, in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on abuses of power within the Russian judiciary.
Further back, it can be traced to 2006, when former KGB officer Alexander Litvinenko was poisoned. Alexander Litvinenko frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
As with the Navalny case, such poisonings often backfire.
In 2004, Anna Politkovskaya, a liberal journalist with the newspaper Novaya Gazeta, was poisoned on a flight from Moscow to Beslan, though she survived, but two years later she was shot dead in her apartment elevator.
As Putin himself said, her death caused significant damage to the Russian government's image.
This does not exonerate the Kremlin in any way.
Whether or not Putin personally ordered it, the system he created allows such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, a farce involving some shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the result the Kremlin wanted, and satisfying their master Putin is the ultimate goal of the lackeys.
Loyalty is the only goal within Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning failed, they would not face punishment.
Because they did this for the president's benefit.
Those seeking evidence of the poisoning may be disappointed.
Despite that, the Kremlin is the culprit.
Western countries must take a clear stance and impose sanctions on Russia, even if it affects their own economies.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All the responsibility in Russia is attributed to him.
